07276nam a22009615i 9780812297348DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780812297348  a(DE-B1597)563402  a(OCoLC)1192542224  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aCB465 7aHIS0380002bisacsh04a551.46223/eng02aA World at Sea :bMaritime Practices and Global History /ced. by Lauren Benton, Nathan Perl-Rosenthal. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Americas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Making Maritime history Global -- tPart I. Currents -- tChapter 1. Why did anyone Go to sea? structures of Maritime enlistment from family Traditions to Violent coercion -- tChapter 2. Between the company and Koxinga: Territorial Waters, Trade, and War over deerskins -- tChapter 3. “The law is the lord of the sea”: Maritime law as Global Maritime history -- tPart II. Dispatches -- tChapter 4. reading cargoes: letters and the Problem of nationality in the age of Privateering -- tChapter 5. sailors, states, and the creation of nautical Knowledge -- tChapter 6. indigenous Maritime Travelers and Knowledge Production -- tPart III. Thresholds -- tChapter 7. Maritime Marronage in colonial Borderlands -- tChapter 8. sovereignty at the Water’s edge: Japan’s opening as coastal encounter -- tChapter 9. Working Women Who Got Wet: a Global survey of Women in Premodern and early Modern fisheries -- tAfterword: land- sea regimes in World history -- tNotes -- tList of contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe past twenty-five years have brought a dramatic expansion of scholarship in maritime history, including new research on piracy, long-distance trade, and seafaring cultures. Yet maritime history still inhabits an isolated corner of world history, according to editors Lauren Benton and Nathan Perl-Rosenthal. Benton and Perl-Rosenthal urge historians to place the relationship between maritime and terrestrial processes at the center of the field and to analyze the links between global maritime practices and major transformations in world history.A World at Sea consists of nine original essays that sharpen and expand our understanding of practices and processes across the land-sea divide and the way they influenced global change. The first section highlights the regulatory order of the seas as shaped by strategies of land-based polities and their agents and by conflicts at sea. The second section studies documentary practices that aggregated and conveyed information about sea voyages and encounters, and it traces the wide-ranging impact of the explosion of new information about the maritime world. Probing the political symbolism of the land-sea divide as a threshold of power, the last section features essays that examine the relationship between littoral geographies and sociolegal practices spanning land and sea. Maritime history, the contributors show, matters because the oceans were key sites of experimentation, innovation, and disruption that reflected and sparked wide-ranging global change.Contributors: Lauren Benton, Adam Clulow, Xing Hang, David Igler, Jeppe Mulich, Lisa Norling, Nathan Perl-Rosenthal, Carla Rahn Phillips, Catherine Phipps, Matthew Raffety, Margaret Schotte.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGlobalizationxHistory. 0aMaritime lawxHistory. 0aNaval art and sciencexHistory. 0aNavigationxHistory. 0aOcean and civilizationxHistory. 0aWorld history. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh  aEuropean His